         <head type="main">Assiniboine</head>
         <div type="additional">
            <p>
At the beginning of the nineteenth century, the many bands of the Assiniboines made their home across the northern Great Plains, some moving southward into the current states of Montana and North Dakota. Like many other Native peoples of the Plains, much of their way of life was mobile—accustomed to horseback riding, quickly setting up and taking down tepees while hunting and following vast buffalo herds. These pictures, taken nearly a century after the Corps of Discovery, show that the Assiniboines' affinity with horses and preference for portable tepees persisted even during the early reservation years. The Assiniboines were active traders and renowned fighters; exchanging goods with the Mandans and European traders on the Missouri River, skirmishing with the Blackfoot and Gros Ventre, and closely allied with the Plains Cree. Nearly half of the Assiniboine people were wiped out by smallpox prior to their encounter with the Corps of Discovery, and half of those succumbed to an epidemic of measles and whooping cough a generation later. The Assiniboines have endured, however, with their resilient culture undergoing some changes but remaining rich and distinctive. Today they live on reserves in Canada and the Fort Belknap and Fort Peck reservations in the United States.<lb/>
               <lb/>
            </p>
